üìò Experiment ‚Äì 08 : Integrate Kubernetes and Docker
AIM

To integrate Kubernetes with Docker and orchestrate containerized applications using Pods, Deployments, and Services.


Exp-08

OBJECTIVE

Enable Kubernetes inside Docker Desktop

Use kubectl CLI to interact with the Kubernetes cluster

Understand how Kubernetes runs as a single-node cluster inside Docker

Learn how to switch contexts and verify cluster installation


Exp-08

SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS

Docker Desktop (Windows/macOS) or Docker Engine (Linux)

Kubernetes enabled (Minikube OR Docker Desktop Kubernetes)

kubectl command-line tool

Code editor (VS Code recommended)

Sample containerized application


Exp-08

üöÄ THEORY SUMMARY

According to the PDF:

Docker Desktop includes a built-in single-node Kubernetes cluster (page 1).

It runs inside Docker containers for lightweight local testing.

Kubernetes allows deploying workloads in parallel with Docker containers.

Kubernetes inside Docker Desktop runs locally, not configurable, and is only meant for learning/testing.


Exp-08

üßë‚Äçüîß LAB PROCEDURE
1. Enable Kubernetes in Docker Desktop

Steps from the PDF (page 1):

Open Docker Desktop Dashboard

Go to Settings

Click the Kubernetes tab

Toggle Enable Kubernetes

Click Apply


Exp-08

Docker Desktop will now:

Pull required Kubernetes system images

Set up the Kubernetes cluster

Install kubectl automatically

2. Check kubectl Installation

kubectl is installed at:

Mac: /usr/local/bin/kubectl

Windows:

C:\Program Files\Docker\Docker\resources\bin\kubectl.exe


Linux: install manually if needed


Exp-08

3. Verify Kubernetes Availability

To check Kubernetes version:

kubectl version


To confirm nodes:

kubectl get nodes


(Shows docker-desktop node if installed correctly.)


Exp-08

4. Working With kubectl Contexts

If kubectl points to another cluster (like Minikube), switch it:

View available contexts:
kubectl config get-contexts

Switch to Docker Desktop Kubernetes:
kubectl config use-context docker-desktop


Exp-08

5. If Context Appears Empty

PDF suggests (page 3):

Try running in PowerShell or Command Prompt

Set KUBECONFIG to your kube config file
Example:

setx KUBECONFIG "%USERPROFILE%\.kube\config"


Exp-08

6. Reset Kubernetes (Optional)

If Kubernetes breaks or an update is needed:

Docker Desktop ‚Üí Settings ‚Üí Kubernetes ‚Üí
Reset Kubernetes Cluster


Exp-08

üß™ VERIFY INSTALLATION

Run:

kubectl get nodes


Expected output:

NAME              STATUS   ROLES    AGE   VERSION
docker-desktop    Ready    master   Xd    vX.X.X


This confirms Kubernetes integration with Docker is successful.
